<paragraph id="CE4036FAAA69FFD9B0F5B3C5FA70F469" blockId="14.[190,1440,1016,1107]" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">
Like 
<taxonomicName id="09FF4D79AA69FFD9B135B3C4FE19F42A" baseAuthorityName="Kluge" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[294,505,1017,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Borinquena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexta">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B135B3C4FE19F42A" box="[294,505,1017,1040]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Borinquena sexta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="09FF4D79AA69FFD9B226B3C5FC86F42A" baseAuthorityName="Kluge" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[565,870,1016,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Turquinophlebia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B226B3C5FC86F42A" box="[565,870,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Turquinophlebia grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the species was described from specimens collected in 
<collectingRegion id="0C3BF818AA69FFD9B134B427FE98F408" box="[295,376,1050,1074]" country="Puerto Rico" name="Arroyo" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Arroyo</collectingRegion>
Paco. It resembles 
<taxonomicName id="09FF4D79AA69FFD9B240B427FD2DF408" baseAuthorityName="Kluge" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[595,717,1050,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Turquinophlebia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B240B427FD2DF408" box="[595,717,1050,1074]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">T. grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with basally broadened gills, but in 
<taxonomicName id="09FF4D79AA69FFD9B47FB427FAF6F408" authorityName="Kluge" authorityYear="1993" box="[1132,1302,1050,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Poecilophlebia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B47FB427FAF6F408" box="[1132,1302,1050,1074]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Poecilophlebia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the labrum has an anteromedian margin with denticles. The tibiae of the hind legs are flat and ventrally concave.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="86E56571AA69FFD9B0D3B451FBD5F4C2" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="CE4036FAAA69FFD9B0D3B451FD09F49F" blockId="14.[192,1440,1132,1272]" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B0D3B451FED5F4BE" bold="true" box="[192,309,1132,1156]" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Ecology.</emphasis>
This species is found in cold water habitats at elevations between 680 and 
<quantity id="09079B1FAA69FFD9B4F2B451FADFF4BE" box="[1249,1343,1132,1156]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" unit="m" value="1200.0">1200 m</quantity>
. Recent research indicates a preference for leaf packs
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE4036FAAA69FFD9B0D3B482FBD5F4C2" blockId="14.[192,1440,1132,1272]" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B0D3B482FDF6F4ED" bold="true" box="[192,534,1215,1239]" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="09FF4D79AA69FFD9B20EB482FCF4F4EC" baseAuthorityName="Kluge" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[541,788,1215,1239]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Poecilophlebia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacoi">
<emphasis id="FC8BEAE8AA69FFD9B20EB482FCF4F4EC" box="[541,788,1215,1239]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Poecilophlebia pacoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known only from the Turquino Massif in the provinces of 
<collectingRegion id="0C3BF818AA69FFD9B19BB4DDFD81F4C2" box="[392,609,1248,1272]" country="Cuba" name="Santiago de Cuba" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Santiago de Cuba</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="0C3BF818AA69FFD9B28EB4DDFCE6F4C2" box="[669,774,1248,1272]" country="Cuba" name="Granma" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Granma</collectingRegion>
, Eastern Region (
<figureCitation id="56C42A7FAA69FFD9B3CCB4DDFBC7F4C2" box="[991,1063,1248,1272]" captionStart="Figures 6–9" captionStartId="36.[192,286,1875,1897]" captionTargetBox="[329,1297,236,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-55@36.[291,1309,235,1867]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figures 6–9. Distribution records for Ephemeroptera in Cuba.6) Paracloeodes lilliputian. 7) Farrodes bimaculatus. 8) Hagenulus caligatus, H. morrisonae. 9) Borinquena sexta, Turquinophlebia grandis, Poecilophlebia pacoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5170695" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5170695/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="13">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
